<!-- SECTION_1_START -->
## 1. Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

### 1.1 What is Node.js?

**Node.js** is an **open-source, cross-platform, server-side JavaScript runtime environment** that executes JavaScript code outside the confines of a web browser. It is built on **Google Chrome's V8 JavaScript Engine** and uses an **event-driven, non-blocking I/O architecture**, making it particularly well-suited for building highly scalable, real-time, network-driven applications.

> [!NOTE]
> **KTU Syllabus Definition:**
> *Node.js is a server-side platform built on Google Chrome's JavaScript Engine (V8) for building fast, scalable network applications. It uses an event-driven, non-blocking I/O model that makes it lightweight and efficient.*

> [!IMPORTANT]
> Node.js is **NOT** a programming language. It is a **runtime environment** that allows JavaScript to be executed on the server. The language is JavaScript; Node.js is the engine/platform that runs it.

---

### 1.2 Conceptual Analogy — The Restaurant Kitchen

Imagine a busy restaurant kitchen:

| Restaurant Concept | Node.js Equivalent |
|--------------------|--------------------|
| **Head Chef (Takes Orders)** | **Event Loop** — continuously checks for new tasks |
| **Waiter (Single Person)** | **Single Threaded Event Loop** — one person managing multiple orders |
| **Cooking on Stove (Long Task)** | **Thread Pool / Worker Threads** — delegated heavy work |
| **Order Slip on Counter** | **Event Queue** — tasks waiting to be picked up |
| **Dish Ready Callback** | **Callback Function** — notifies when task completes |

**Real-world analogy explained:**
In a traditional server (like Apache with PHP), every new request creates a new thread (think: hiring a new chef for every customer). This is slow and resource-heavy.

In **Node.js**, there is **only ONE chef (the event loop)**. The chef takes the order, hands it to the stove (worker thread), and immediately moves to the next customer. When the dish is ready, the chef is notified (via a callback) and serves it. This is the essence of **non-blocking, asynchronous, event-driven** architecture.

---

### 1.3 Key Terminology — Formal Definitions

| Term | Formal Definition |
|------|-------------------|
| **V8 Engine** | The high-performance JavaScript and WebAssembly engine written in C++ that compiles JavaScript directly into machine code. |
| **Event Loop** | A constantly running process that monitors the call stack and callback queue, executing callbacks when the stack is empty. |
| **Non-Blocking I/O** | An I/O model where the program does not halt execution while waiting for I/O operations; instead, it continues and is notified upon completion. |
| **Single-Threaded** | Refers to the fact that a single instance of the Node.js event loop runs on a single main thread, though background workers (libuv thread pool) handle I/O. |
| **libuv** | A C library that provides the **event loop**, **thread pool**, and **asynchronous I/O** capabilities for Node.js. |
| **NPM (Node Package Manager)** | The default package manager for Node.js and the world's largest software registry. |
| **Express.js** | A minimal, fast, and unopinionated **web application framework for Node.js** that provides robust features for web and mobile applications. |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **High-Yield Fact for KTU Exams:**
> Node.js was created by **Ryan Dahl** in **2009**. It uses the **V8 engine** developed by **Google** for the Chrome browser. The current stable LTS versions follow the naming convention `Node.js v20.x` / `v22.x`.

---

### 1.4 Why Node.js? — The Motivation

Traditional server-side platforms (e.g., PHP, Java with thread-per-request models) suffer from the **C10K problem** — handling **10,000+ concurrent connections** efficiently. Node.js solves this through its asynchronous architecture.

> [!NOTE]
> **Core Advantages of Node.js:**
> 1. **Asynchronous & Non-Blocking** — No thread is wasted waiting.
> 2. **Extremely Fast** — V8 compiles JS to native machine code.
> 3. **Single Language (JavaScript)** — Both client-side and server-side.
> 4. **NPM Ecosystem** — Over 2 million packages available.
> 5. **Highly Scalable** — Ideal for real-time apps (chat, IoT, streaming).
> 6. **Cross-Platform** — Runs on Windows, macOS, Linux.

<!-- SECTION_1_END -->

<!-- SECTION_2_START -->
## 2. Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Cheat Sheet

### 2.1 The Architecture of Node.js — Layer-by-Layer Breakdown

Node.js uses a **multi-layered architecture**. From top to bottom, requests flow through:

```
┌─────────────────────────────────────────┐
│  Layer 1: JavaScript Application Code  │  ← User-written .js files
├─────────────────────────────────────────┤
│  Layer 2: Node.js Core APIs (Built-in) │  ← fs, http, path, events
├─────────────────────────────────────────┤
│  Layer 3: Node.js Bindings (C/C++)     │  ← Connect JS to C++ libs
├─────────────────────────────────────────┤
│  Layer 4: V8 Engine + libuv            │  ← JS execution + Event Loop
└─────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

---

### 2.2 Core Architectural Components

#### A) The V8 JavaScript Engine
- Developed by Google for Chrome.
- Written in **C++**.
- Implements **ECMAScript** (the JavaScript standard).
- Uses **JIT (Just-In-Time) compilation** — converts JS into machine code at runtime.
- Includes a **heap memory allocator**, **garbage collector**, and **compiler**.

#### B) libuv Library
- A **C library** that is the backbone of Node.js asynchronous I/O.
- Provides:
  - The **Event Loop**.
  - A **Thread Pool** (default size: **4 threads**).
  - **Asynchronous I/O operations** for files, DNS, network, pipes.
  - **Signal handling**, **child processes**, and **worker threads**.

#### C) The Event Loop (The Heart of Node.js)
The event loop is a **semi-infinite loop** that processes callbacks. It has **6 distinct phases**, executed in strict order:

| Phase | Name | Responsibility |
|-------|------|----------------|
| **1** | **Timers** | Executes callbacks scheduled by `setTimeout()` and `setInterval()`. |
| **2** | **Pending Callbacks** | Executes I/O callbacks deferred from previous iteration. |
| **3** | **Idle, Prepare** | Internal use only — prepares for next poll phase. |
| **4** | **Poll** | Retrieves new I/O events; executes I/O-related callbacks. **Most work happens here.** |
| **5** | **Check** | Executes callbacks scheduled by `setImmediate()`. |
| **6** | **Close Callbacks** | Executes close callbacks (e.g., `socket.on('close', ...)`). |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Between each phase, the event loop also checks the `process.nextTick()` queue and the Promise microtask queue.** These have higher priority than regular I/O callbacks.

#### D) Thread Pool
- Node.js uses **libuv's thread pool** for blocking I/O operations:
  - File system operations (`fs.readFile`)
  - DNS lookups (`dns.lookup`)
  - CPU-intensive tasks (can use `Worker Threads` for parallel computation)
- Default pool size: **4 threads**, configurable via `UV_THREADPOOL_SIZE` environment variable (max: **1024**).

#### E) Node.js Core Modules (Built-in)
- **`http`** — Create HTTP servers and clients.
- **`fs`** — File system operations.
- **`path`** — Handle and transform file paths.
- **`events`** — Build event-driven architecture using `EventEmitter`.
- **`stream`** — Handle streaming data.
- **`os`** — Operating system-related utility methods.
- **`url`** — URL parsing utilities.

---

### 2.3 Working with Node.js — Practical Foundations

#### A) Installation & Verification
- **Download:** [https://nodejs.org/](https://nodejs.org/)
- **Verify installation:**
```bash
node -v
npm -v
```

#### B) Running a Node.js Script
1. Create a file `app.js`:
```javascript
console.log("Hello from Node.js!");
```
2. Execute:
```bash
node app.js
```

#### C) REPL (Read-Eval-Print Loop)
- Launch by typing `node` in the terminal.
- Test JavaScript code interactively.
- Useful for debugging and learning.

#### D) Node.js Global Objects
| Object | Description |
|--------|-------------|
| `global` | The global namespace object (like `window` in browsers). |
| `__dirname` | The directory name of the current module. |
| `__filename` | The file name of the current module. |
| `process` | Provides info about, and control over, the current Node.js process. |
| `Buffer` | Used to handle binary data. |
| `require()` | Function to import modules (CommonJS). |
| `module` | Reference to the current module. |
| `exports` | Object that is exported from the current module. |

#### E) Modules in Node.js
Node.js uses the **CommonJS module system** by default.

**Creating a custom module** (`math.js`):
```javascript
function add(a, b) {
    return a + b;
}
function subtract(a, b) {
    return a - b;
}
module.exports = { add, subtract };
```

**Importing a module** (`app.js`):
```javascript
const math = require('./math');
console.log(math.add(5, 3));      // Output: 8
console.log(math.subtract(10, 4)); // Output: 6
```

> [!NOTE]
> Node.js now also supports **ES Modules** (`.mjs` or `"type": "module"` in `package.json`) using `import`/`export` syntax.

#### F) Built-in `http` Module — Building a Web Server
```javascript
const http = require('http');

const server = http.createServer((req, res) => {
    res.statusCode = 200;
    res.setHeader('Content-Type', 'text/plain');
    res.end('Hello, World!\n');
});

server.listen(3000, () => {
    console.log('Server running at http://localhost:3000/');
});
```

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **The `req` object is an instance of `http.IncomingMessage`**, and **`res` is an instance of `http.ServerResponse`**.

#### G) NPM (Node Package Manager)
- **Initialize a project:**
```bash
npm init
```
- **Install a package locally:**
```bash
npm install express
```
- **Install a package globally:**
```bash
npm install -g nodemon
```
- **Install as dev dependency:**
```bash
npm install --save-dev jest
```
- The installed packages go into the `node_modules/` folder, and the dependencies are recorded in `package.json`.

---

### 2.4 Adding Express to Node.js

#### A) What is Express.js?
- A **fast, minimalist web framework** for Node.js.
- Built on top of Node's built-in `http` module.
- Provides a **thin layer of fundamental web application features** without obscuring Node.js features.
- Often called the **de facto standard** server framework for Node.js.

#### B) Installation
```bash
npm install express
```

#### C) A Minimal Express Server
```javascript
const express = require('express');
const app = express();
const PORT = 3000;

// Define a route
app.get('/', (req, res) => {
    res.send('Welcome to Express!');
});

// Start the server
app.listen(PORT, () => {
    console.log(`Server running on http://localhost:${PORT}`);
});
```

#### D) Core Express Concepts

| Concept | Description | Example |
|---------|-------------|---------|
| **Application (`app`)** | The main Express object that has methods for routing, configuring middleware, etc. | `const app = express();` |
| **Routing** | Defines how the app responds to a client request at a particular endpoint. | `app.get('/path', handler);` |
| **Middleware** | Functions that have access to `req`, `res`, and the `next()` function. | `app.use(express.json());` |
| **Request (`req`)** | Represents the HTTP request. Properties: `req.body`, `req.params`, `req.query`, `req.headers`. | `req.query.name` |
| **Response (`res`)** | Represents the HTTP response. Methods: `res.send()`, `res.json()`, `res.status()`. | `res.json({ msg: 'OK' });` |
| **Router** | A mini Express application that handles routes modularly. | `const router = express.Router();` |

#### E) HTTP Methods in Express
```javascript
app.get('/users', (req, res) => { /* READ */ });
app.post('/users', (req, res) => { /* CREATE */ });
app.put('/users/:id', (req, res) => { /* UPDATE */ });
app.delete('/users/:id', (req, res) => { /* DELETE */ });
app.patch('/users/:id', (req, res) => { /* PARTIAL UPDATE */ });
```

#### F) Middleware Functions — The Heart of Express
Middleware functions execute in the request-response cycle and can:
1. Execute any code.
2. Modify `req` and `res` objects.
3. End the request-response cycle (`res.send()`).
4. Call the next middleware in the stack (`next()`).

**Example — Custom Middleware:**
```javascript
const logger = (req, res, next) => {
    console.log(`${req.method} ${req.url} - ${new Date().toISOString()}`);
    next(); // Pass control to the next middleware
};
app.use(logger);
```

**Example — Built-in and Third-party Middleware:**
```javascript
// Built-in: Parse JSON bodies
app.use(express.json());

// Built-in: Parse URL-encoded bodies
app.use(express.urlencoded({ extended: true }));

// Third-party: Serve static files
app.use(express.static('public'));
```

> [!NOTE]
> The **order of middleware matters!** Middleware functions are executed in the order they are defined using `app.use()`.

#### G) Route Parameters
```javascript
app.get('/users/:id', (req, res) => {
    const userId = req.params.id;
    res.send(`User ID: ${userId}`);
});
// Visit: http://localhost:3000/users/42
```

#### H) Query Strings
```javascript
app.get('/search', (req, res) => {
    const { q, page } = req.query;
    res.json({ query: q, page: page || 1 });
});
// Visit: http://localhost:3000/search?q=nodejs&page=2
```

#### I) Modular Routing with `express.Router`
**Create `routes/users.js`:**
```javascript
const express = require('express');
const router = express.Router();

router.get('/', (req, res) => res.send('All Users'));
router.get('/:id', (req, res) => res.send(`User ${req.params.id}`));
router.post('/', (req, res) => res.status(201).send('User Created'));

module.exports = router;
```

**In `app.js`:**
```javascript
const userRoutes = require('./routes/users');
app.use('/users', userRoutes);
```

#### J) Error Handling in Express
```javascript
// 404 Handler (no route matched)
app.use((req, res, next) => {
    res.status(404).send('Page Not Found');
});

// Global Error Handler (must have 4 arguments)
app.use((err, req, res, next) => {
    console.error(err.stack);
    res.status(500).send('Something broke!');
});
```

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Error-handling middleware MUST be defined LAST** and **MUST have exactly 4 parameters** `(err, req, res, next)` so Express can identify it as an error handler.

#### K) Serving Static Files
```javascript
app.use(express.static('public'));
// Files in 'public' folder are served at root URL
// public/index.html  ->  http://localhost:3000/index.html
// public/css/style.css -> http://localhost:3000/css/style.css
```

---

### 2.5 Comparison: Node.js `http` vs Express.js

| Feature | Node.js `http` | Express.js |
|---------|----------------|------------|
| **Routing** | Manual, verbose | `app.get()`, `app.post()` — clean |
| **Middleware Support** | No native support | First-class citizen |
| **Static File Serving** | Manual file reading | `express.static()` |
| **Request Body Parsing** | Manual stream handling | `express.json()`, `express.urlencoded()` |
| **Code Volume** | ~10+ lines for a server | ~5 lines for a server |
| **Performance** | Slightly faster (no abstraction) | Negligible overhead |
| **Best Use Case** | Low-level HTTP, custom protocols | REST APIs, web apps |

<!-- SECTION_2_END -->

<!-- SECTION_3_START -->
## 3. Step-by-Step Analytical Walkthroughs

### 3.1 Step-by-Step: Tracing a Request Through the Node.js Event Loop

Let us trace what happens when a client makes an HTTP request to a Node.js server with a file read operation.

**Scenario:** A client requests `http://localhost:3000/file`, and the server reads a file from disk before responding.

**Server Code:**
```javascript
const http = require('http');
const fs = require('fs');

const server = http.createServer((req, res) => {
    console.log('1. Request received');

    fs.readFile('data.txt', (err, data) => {
        console.log('3. File read complete');
        res.end(data);
    });

    console.log('2. Continuing to next task');
});

server.listen(3000);
```

**Step-by-step execution trace:**

| Step | Action | Output |
|------|--------|--------|
| **1** | Client sends GET request. | (Network event) |
| **2** | Event Loop picks up the request and invokes the callback. | `"1. Request received"` |
| **3** | `fs.readFile()` is called — it is **non-blocking**, so it sends the file-read task to the **libuv thread pool**. | — |
| **4** | Execution continues without waiting. | `"2. Continuing to next task"` |
| **5** | Event Loop returns to waiting for more events. | — |
| **6** | A libuv worker thread completes the file read. The callback is pushed into the **Poll phase queue**. | — |
| **7** | Event Loop reaches the **Poll phase**, dequeues the callback, and runs it. | `"3. File read complete"` |
| **8** | `res.end(data)` sends the response back to the client. | (HTTP response sent) |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> The order of console output will be: **1 → 2 → 3** (NOT 1 → 3 → 2). This is the essence of **non-blocking I/O**.

---

### 3.2 Step-by-Step: Building and Testing a Full Express REST API

**Step 1 — Initialize the project:**
```bash
mkdir student-api
cd student-api
npm init -y
```

**Step 2 — Install Express:**
```bash
npm install express
```

**Step 3 — Create `app.js`:**
```javascript
const express = require('express');
const app = express();
const PORT = 3000;

// In-memory data store
let students = [
    { id: 1, name: 'Arjun', branch: 'CSE' },
    { id: 2, name: 'Meera', branch: 'ECE' }
];

// Middleware to parse JSON
app.use(express.json());

// Logger middleware
app.use((req, res, next) => {
    console.log(`${new Date().toISOString()} - ${req.method} ${req.url}`);
    next();
});

// READ all students
app.get('/api/students', (req, res) => {
    res.json(students);
});

// READ single student
app.get('/api/students/:id', (req, res) => {
    const student = students.find(s => s.id === parseInt(req.params.id));
    if (!student) return res.status(404).json({ error: 'Not Found' });
    res.json(student);
});

// CREATE a student
app.post('/api/students', (req, res) => {
    const newStudent = {
        id: students.length + 1,
        name: req.body.name,
        branch: req.body.branch
    };
    students.push(newStudent);
    res.status(201).json(newStudent);
});

// UPDATE a student
app.put('/api/students/:id', (req, res) => {
    const student = students.find(s => s.id === parseInt(req.params.id));
    if (!student) return res.status(404).json({ error: 'Not Found' });
    student.name = req.body.name || student.name;
    student.branch = req.body.branch || student.branch;
    res.json(student);
});

// DELETE a student
app.delete('/api/students/:id', (req, res) => {
    const index = students.findIndex(s => s.id === parseInt(req.params.id));
    if (index === -1) return res.status(404).json({ error: 'Not Found' });
    students.splice(index, 1);
    res.status(204).send();
});

app.listen(PORT, () => {
    console.log(`Server running on http://localhost:${PORT}`);
});
```

**Step 4 — Test with cURL:**
```bash
# GET all
curl http://localhost:3000/api/students

# GET one
curl http://localhost:3000/api/students/1

# POST a new student
curl -X POST http://localhost:3000/api/students \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '{"name":"Rahul","branch":"ME"}'

# DELETE a student
curl -X DELETE http://localhost:3000/api/students/1
```

---

### 3.3 Step-by-Step: Middleware Execution Flow

Consider this Express app:
```javascript
app.use((req, res, next) => { console.log('A'); next(); });
app.use((req, res, next) => { console.log('B'); next(); });

app.get('/test', (req, res, next) => { console.log('C'); next(); },
        (req, res) => { console.log('D'); res.send('Done'); });

app.use((req, res) => { console.log('E'); res.status(404).send('404'); });
```

**Execution trace for GET `/test`:**

$$
\begin{aligned}
\text{Request} \rightarrow &\ \text{Middleware A} \rightarrow \text{Middleware B} \rightarrow \\
&\ \text{Route Handler C} \rightarrow \text{Route Handler D} \rightarrow \text{Response Sent}
\end{aligned}
$$

**Output:** `A`, `B`, `C`, `D`

**Execution trace for GET `/unknown`:**

$$
\begin{aligned}
\text{Request} \rightarrow &\ \text{Middleware A} \rightarrow \text{Middleware B} \rightarrow \\
&\ \text{(no route matched)} \rightarrow \text{404 Handler E} \rightarrow \text{Response Sent}
\end{aligned}
$$

**Output:** `A`, `B`, `E`

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Middleware always runs first.** Route handlers only execute if the URL matches. If no route matches, the request falls through to the next middleware (e.g., a 404 handler).

---

### 3.4 Step-by-Step: Deriving Why Node.js is Non-Blocking

**Conceptual flow of a blocking (PHP/Apache-style) server:**

$$
T_{\text{total}} = \sum_{i=1}^{n} T_{\text{request}_i}
$$

Where each $T_{\text{request}_i}$ includes I/O wait time. If $n = 10000$ requests and each takes $100$ ms, total = **1,000,000 ms = 16.67 minutes**.

**Conceptual flow of a non-blocking (Node.js) server:**

$$
T_{\text{total}} \approx \max(T_{\text{request}_i}) \cdot k
$$

Since the event loop processes I/O asynchronously, the bottleneck is no longer the number of requests, but rather the longest single operation. With a **single thread**, Node.js can handle **tens of thousands** of concurrent connections in roughly the time it takes to handle one.

> [!NOTE]
> This is why Node.js is called a **"concurrency model"**, not a **"parallelism model"**. Concurrency handles many tasks at once via context switching; parallelism executes multiple tasks simultaneously using multiple CPU cores.

