## 4. Structural Diagrams & Schematics

### 4.1 Node.js High-Level Architecture (Block Diagram)

```mermaid
flowchart TB
    appCode["JavaScript Application Code<br>(User-written .js files)"]
    nodeAPI["Node.js Core APIs<br>http, fs, path, events, stream"]
    bindings["Node.js Bindings<br>C++ Connector Layer"]
    v8["V8 Engine<br>JavaScript Compiler and Runtime"]
    libuv["libuv Library<br>Event Loop + Thread Pool + Async I/O"]
    os["Operating System<br>Kernel-Level I/O Operations"]

    appCode --> nodeAPI
    nodeAPI --> bindings
    bindings --> v8
    bindings --> libuv
    v8 --> bindings
    libuv --> os
    os --> libuv
    libuv --> bindings
    bindings --> nodeAPI
    nodeAPI --> appCode
```

---

### 4.2 Event Loop Phases — Cyclic Flow

```mermaid
flowchart LR
    start(["Start Event Loop Iteration"]) --> timers["Phase 1: Timers<br>setTimeout, setInterval"]
    timers --> pending["Phase 2: Pending Callbacks<br>Deferred I/O Callbacks"]
    pending --> idle["Phase 3: Idle, Prepare<br>Internal Phase"]
    idle --> poll["Phase 4: Poll<br>New I/O Events & Callbacks"]
    poll --> check["Phase 5: Check<br>setImmediate Callbacks"]
    check --> close["Phase 6: Close Callbacks<br>socket.on close etc"]
    close --> start
```

> [!NOTE]
> The `process.nextTick()` queue and the **Promise microtask queue** are processed **between every phase transition**, which means they always run before the next I/O callback.

---

### 4.3 Node.js Request Handling — Non-Blocking Flow

```mermaid
sequenceDiagram
    participant Client as Client Browser
    participant EL as Event Loop
    participant TP as libuv Thread Pool
    participant FS as File System

    Client->>EL: 1. HTTP Request Received
    activate EL
    EL->>EL: 2. Execute request handler
    EL->>TP: 3. Offload fs.readFile (non-blocking)
    deactivate EL
    Note over EL: Event Loop is FREE for next request
    Client->>EL: 4. Another Request Received
    activate EL
    EL->>EL: 5. Handle second request
    deactivate EL
    TP->>FS: 6. Read file from disk
    FS-->>TP: 7. File data returned
    TP-->>EL: 8. Push callback to queue
    EL->>Client: 9. Send response (data)
    EL->>Client: 10. Send response (request 2)
```

---

### 4.4 Express.js Middleware Pipeline

```mermaid
flowchart LR
    req(["Incoming HTTP Request"]) --> m1["Middleware 1<br>express.json()"]
    m1 --> m2["Middleware 2<br>Logger"]
    m2 --> m3["Middleware 3<br>express.static()"]
    m3 --> r1{"Route<br>Matched?"}
    r1 -- "Yes" --> rh["Route Handler<br>app.get/post/put/delete"]
    r1 -- "No" --> e1["404 Handler<br>app.use fallback"]
    rh --> res(["HTTP Response Sent"])
    e1 --> res
```

> [!IMPORTANT]
> Middleware functions can short-circuit the pipeline by calling `res.send()` or `res.json()` and **NOT** calling `next()`. This is a common pitfall in Express development.

---

### 4.5 Express Application Structure (Recommended Layout)

```mermaid
flowchart TB
    root["Project Root<br>package.json, server.js"]
    routes["routes/<br>Route Definitions"]
    controllers["controllers/<br>Business Logic"]
    models["models/<br>Data Models and DB"]
    middleware["middleware/<br>Custom Middleware"]
    config["config/<br>Environment Configs"]
    utils["utils/<br>Helper Functions"]

    root --> routes
    root --> controllers
    root --> models
    root --> middleware
    root --> config
    root --> utils
    routes --> controllers
    controllers --> models
    controllers --> utils
```

