#### Part (a) — Architecture of Node.js (7 marks)

The architecture of Node.js is built on a **layered model** consisting of the following key components:

**1. JavaScript Application Layer (Top)**
- The user's JavaScript code resides here.
- It uses Node.js core APIs and third-party modules (via NPM).

**2. Node.js Core APIs (Built-in Modules)**
- Modules like `http`, `fs`, `path`, `events`, `stream` provide essential functionality.
- These are written in JavaScript and C++.

**3. Node.js Bindings**
- A C++ binding layer that connects JavaScript to the underlying C++ libraries.
- Uses **V8's C++ API** to expose native functions to JS code.

**4. V8 JavaScript Engine**
- Compiles and executes JavaScript using **JIT compilation**.
- Manages memory via the **heap** and **garbage collector**.

**5. libuv Library (The Foundation)**
- Written in C, libuv provides:
  - The **event loop** that orchestrates asynchronous operations.
  - A **thread pool** (default 4 threads) for blocking I/O.
  - **Cross-platform asynchronous I/O** abstractions for files, networking, DNS, etc.

**Architecture Flow:**

$$
\text{JS Code} \rightarrow \text{Node.js Core APIs} \rightarrow \text{Bindings} \rightarrow \{\text{V8} \parallel \text{libuv}\} \rightarrow \text{OS}
$$

**Diagram:**

```mermaid
flowchart TB
    layer1["JS Application Code"]
    layer2["Node.js Core APIs<br>http, fs, path, events"]
    layer3["Node.js Bindings (C++)"]
    layer4a["V8 Engine"]
    layer4b["libuv Library<br>Event Loop + Thread Pool"]
    layer5["Operating System"]

    layer1 --> layer2
    layer2 --> layer3
    layer3 --> layer4a
    layer3 --> layer4b
    layer4a --> layer5
    layer4b --> layer5
```

#### Part (b) — Six Phases of the Event Loop (7 marks)

The event loop is the **core of Node.js's asynchronous behavior**. It cycles through **six phases** in a fixed order on every iteration:

| # | Phase | Purpose |
|---|-------|---------|
| 1 | **Timers** | Executes callbacks scheduled by `setTimeout()` and `setInterval()`. |
| 2 | **Pending Callbacks** | Runs I/O callbacks that were deferred from the previous loop iteration. |
| 3 | **Idle, Prepare** | Internal use — Node.js uses this for its own housekeeping. |
| 4 | **Poll** | The most important phase: fetches new I/O events and executes their callbacks. If there are no pending callbacks, it will block here waiting for new I/O. |
| 5 | **Check** | Invokes callbacks registered via `setImmediate()`. |
| 6 | **Close Callbacks** | Executes close event callbacks (e.g., `socket.on('close', ...)`). |

**Important notes:**
- Between each phase, the event loop also processes the **microtask queue** (Promises) and the **`process.nextTick()` queue**.
- `process.nextTick()` and **Promise callbacks** are **not part of the event loop phases** — they run after every phase transition, with `process.nextTick()` having the **highest priority**.

